    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Perplexity Measures"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Perplexity (PPL)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is the standard intrinsic metric for language models. Intuitively, it answers the question: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "on average, how many equally likely choices did the model face at each token position?"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " A model that always predicts the next token correctly has PPL = 1. A model that is completely random over a 10,000-word vocabulary has PPL = 10,000. Real models land somewhere between those extremes."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Perplexity is directly derived from the cross-entropy loss used during training: it is simply "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "e^loss"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". This means you get perplexity for free when you have evaluation loss — no separate computation needed."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Formula"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Given a test sequence "
          },
          {
            "type": "inlineMath",
            "attrs": {
              "latex": "W = w_1, w_2, \\ldots, w_T"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", perplexity is defined as:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{PPL}(W) = \\exp\\!\\left(-\\frac{1}{T}\\sum_{t=1}^{T}\\log P(w_t \\mid w_1,\\ldots,w_{t-1})\\right)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The term inside the exponent is the average negative log-likelihood — exactly the cross-entropy loss "
          },
          {
            "type": "inlineMath",
            "attrs": {
              "latex": "\\mathcal{L}"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". So:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{PPL}(W) = e^{\\mathcal{L}}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When loss uses log base 2 instead of natural log, perplexity equals "
          },
          {
            "type": "inlineMath",
            "attrs": {
              "latex": "2^H"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " where H is the cross-entropy in bits. Both conventions are common; always check which base a library uses."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Three language models with different probability assignments to the same test sentence, showing PPL 15, 80, and 600 respectively"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Computing Perplexity in Python"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import math\n\ndef perplexity_from_probs(token_probs: list[float]) -> float:\n    \"\"\"Compute perplexity from a list of conditional probabilities.\"\"\"\n    log_sum = sum(math.log(p) for p in token_probs)\n    avg_nll = -log_sum / len(token_probs)\n    return math.exp(avg_nll)\n\n# Example: model assigned these probabilities to 4 tokens\nprobs = [0.08, 0.04, 0.12, 0.09]\nprint(f\"Perplexity: {perplexity_from_probs(probs):.1f}\")  # ≈ 15.3\n\n# Equivalently, from cross-entropy loss:\nimport torch\nloss = 2.73  # from model evaluation\nppl = math.exp(loss)\nprint(f\"PPL from loss: {ppl:.1f}\")  # ≈ 15.3"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Evaluating with Hugging Face"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "evaluate"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " library provides a ready-made perplexity metric that handles batching and stride correctly."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import evaluate\nfrom transformers import AutoModelForCausalLM, AutoTokenizer\n\nmodel_id = \"gpt2\"\ntokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_id)\nmodel = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained(model_id)\n\nperplexity = evaluate.load(\"perplexity\", module_type=\"metric\")\n\ntest_texts = [\n    \"The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog.\",\n    \"xkq8f! banana%%%moon random gibberish\",  # should have high PPL\n]\n\nresults = perplexity.compute(\n    predictions=test_texts,\n    model_id=model_id,\n    add_start_token=False,\n)\nprint(results[\"perplexities\"])   # e.g. [42.3, 8921.4]\nprint(results[\"mean_perplexity\"])  # average across all texts"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Stride Trick for Long Sequences"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A model with context window of length L cannot compute "
          },
          {
            "type": "inlineMath",
            "attrs": {
              "latex": "P(w_t \\mid w_1, \\ldots, w_{t-1})"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " for t > L. The standard workaround is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "strided evaluation"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": slide a window of size L over the document, but only score the last "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "stride"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " tokens in each window (the earlier tokens serve as context). Larger stride = faster but noisier; stride = 1 = slowest but most accurate."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nfrom transformers import AutoModelForCausalLM, AutoTokenizer\n\ndef strided_perplexity(text: str, model_id: str = \"gpt2\", stride: int = 512) -> float:\n    tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_id)\n    model = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained(model_id).eval()\n    max_len = model.config.n_positions  # e.g. 1024 for GPT-2\n\n    encodings = tokenizer(text, return_tensors=\"pt\")\n    input_ids = encodings.input_ids[0]\n    T = input_ids.size(0)\n\n    nlls = []\n    for begin in range(0, T, stride):\n        end = min(begin + max_len, T)\n        window = input_ids[begin:end].unsqueeze(0)\n        # Only score tokens we haven't scored yet\n        target_len = end - max(begin, stride)  # avoids double-counting\n        with torch.no_grad():\n            loss = model(window, labels=window).loss\n        nlls.append(loss.item() * target_len)\n\n    ppl = torch.exp(torch.tensor(sum(nlls) / T))\n    return ppl.item()\n\nprint(strided_perplexity(\"The astronaut floated weightlessly.\"))"
          }
        ]
      },
