      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Limitations"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Not comparable across tokenisers."
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " A model using byte-pair encoding with a 50k vocabulary will have different raw PPL than one using character-level tokenisation on the same text. Always compare models with the same tokeniser."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Doesn't measure usefulness."
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " A model fine-tuned to output very low-PPL text (e.g. always generating the most probable continuation) can be boring and useless. PPL measures fluency, not helpfulness."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Sensitive to test set distribution."
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " A model trained on Wikipedia will have low PPL on Wikipedia test splits and high PPL on Twitter data. PPL always measures fit to a specific distribution."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Test data contamination inflates scores."
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " If training data includes the test corpus, PPL will be artificially low — the model has memorised the answers."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Use perplexity to track training progress and compare architectures on the same data. Use downstream task benchmarks (accuracy, BLEU, ROUGE) to assess whether a lower-PPL model is actually more useful."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
